<p><img class="alignleft" style="margin-left: 4px; margin-right: 4px;" title="Muriel Glasgow" src="http://yaktivate.s3.amazonaws.com/unitednationsyak/images/murielglasgow.jpg" alt="" width="110" height="163" /> </td>
<td>
<p align="left">
<p><img class="alignright" title="Alex Prud'homme" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/yaktivate/unitednationsyak/images/Alex_Prudhomme1.jpg" alt="" width="113" height="164" /></p>
<p>Alex Prud’homme has been a journalist and author for over twenty years.<br />
He has written on a wide range of subjects for The New York Times, The New Yorker, Vanity Fair, and Time.  He has authored four books, most notably as co-writer of Julia Child’s memoir, My Life in France, which was a best-seller and inspired half the film “Julie &#038; Julia.” </p>
<table>
<tr>
<td>
His latest book is The Ripple Effect: the Fate of Freshwater in the  Twenty-First Century, was published in 2011, and inspired the documentary film “Last Call at the Oasis.”  Alex Prud’homme lives with his family in Brooklyn, NY.  For more information please see: </p>
<p><a href="http://www.alexprudhomme.com">www.alexprudhomme.com</a></p>
</td>
<td>
